    "refcode_2": "56",
    "refcode_3": "3",
    "refcode_4": "",
    "refcode_short": "AH 56.3",
    "refcode_long": "The Adventist Home, p. 56.3 (Ellen Gould White)",
    "element_type": "p",
    "element_subtype": "standard-indented",
    "content": "These hours of midnight dissipation, in this age of depravity, frequently lead to the ruin of both parties thus engaged. Satan exults and God is dishonored when men and women dishonor themselves. The good name of honor is sacrificed under the spell of this infatuation, and the marriage of such persons cannot be solemnized under the approval of God. They are married because passion moved them, and when the novelty of the affair is over, they will begin to realize what they have done.<sup class=\"chapterendnote\"><a class=\"chapterendnote\">4<span class=\"chapterendnote\"><span class=\"egwlink egwlink_book\" title=\"RH 9-25-1888\" data-link=\"821.9198\">The Review and Herald, September 25, 1888</span>.</span></a></sup>",
